I admire their religion the most, that is what they based their whole being on. Although, all of these witch trials were going on, people were suspected of being involved with witch craft or even being a witch, but they would say they were innocent. It would be a lie if they did not tell the truth and that is a sin. I admire that they hold their religion that high, even if confessing and admitting guilt meant staying alive. The only reason Tituba was not put to death was because she confessed. Even though I admire their religion, I also feel this was their biggest hang-up. Its was good to be religious, but the way religion was portrayed, the puritans made it seem like there is only one way, and it was there way. In the end everyone is to looking up to the same being, so what does it matter what religion you are? Today we have so many different religions, Catholic, Baptist, Episcopal, etc. There are all different, but one in the same. They all give glory to one being. Of course with every religion there are going to be different, but still at the end of the day, its all about one being. My personal opinion probably contradicts everyone else's but yes, I do think there were witches, just because I believe in that stuff. I believe in black magic and witches. It had to originate somewhere. All Tituaba was trying to do was educate them. I think there was so much hysteria over this issue because the puritans did not know exactly what it was. People tend to fear what they dont know. I think if they would have given a chance to Witchery and witch craft they would then be able to form an opinion about whether it was good or bad.
