===from:Marcella Emmett
===date:Thu Sep 11 21:39:56 2003
===subject:Witch in the American Imagination
===message:The Puritans of Masschusetts Bay were an admirable society with many with many good qualities as well as faults. Many of the great and enduring qualities of this society came from their rigid religious beliefs, however many of their hangups came from this same source.  The society that the Purtains built was one dutiful christains who helped one other and was grounded by family unites.  Each person had a place and a role in Puritan society. The rich helped the poor and they even help each other with parenting.  This unity and giving to other was only directed to "their own" however.  The Puritans were very much sepratist and they did not tolerate only with varing religious views.  Those who were different were not welcome and dissenter to the beliefs of the colonies church were banished from the colony or prosecuted.

The question of whether there were witches in the Massachusetts Bay colony has been answered by many to be no.  In the sixteen hundreds people though of many things as being supernatural, a way to explain the unknown and seemimgly misterious happening or bad events.  The serious and restrict nature of the Purtians beliefs did not help this matter.  Women gossiping or child born out of wedlock were signs to them that someone was praticing witchcraft.  They simplfied their world though this and in doing so they accused many innocent people of the crime of black magic.

There was so much mass hysteria surrounding the issue of withcraft because of the combination of the stress and anxiety of war, and the agendas of a few.  This combination started and help fan the flame of the accusations of witchcraft.  Many of the those who were accused of witch craft implicted others in to avoid themselves. Those who were accused often confessed  to save themselves from excution.  This helped stirr the mass hysteria which lead to the death of twenty people.
=========yorg=========
===from:Tiffany Charles
===date:Fri Sep 12 12:42:04 2003
===subject:Witches in the American Imagination
===message:What I admire the most about the Puritans of Massachusetts is how they used religious beliefs to hold their community together. They lived their lives as they believed God had ordained. "The rich and powerful were supposed to take care of those who were poor and powerless." (79) If we today followed that simple statement, I believe we would be much better off as citizens, as a country and as people. On the same token, their biggest hang up was their religion. The Bible is open for interpretation. I believe they took the message from the Bible too seriously. Like the excerpt on page 83, "Childhood in Puritan New England," the readings from the Bible put fear in the eight year old child that she couldn't escape. It just got to be too much. I don't believe there were witches in Massachusetts Bay. I believe it was the misinterpretation of the reading from the Bible that scared everyone into this hysteria. If they couldn't believe or excuse and action away they automatically believed it was the work of some evil being (witch). These so called witches were a majority of women. If these women did things differently or behaved in a different fashion, they had to be witches. Well if that's the case, half of this world would be considered witches.  
=========yorg=========
